 can stream live broadcasts over Wi-Fi and supports all of the biggest streaming services, including Disney+, Netflix, Prime Video, Apple TV+, ITVX, BBC iPlayer, and many more. There are also games and step-by-step fitness workouts included in the telly too.</p><p>Since everything is beamed wirelessly via Wi-Fi to your telly, that means you won't need to worry about an engineer drilling holes into the outside walls of your home (handy if you're renting, or living in an apartment building) and set-up is as easy as plugging in a&nbsp;<em>single power cable</em>&nbsp;to Sky Glass.</p><p>It's also the only device in the lineup that's compatible with Sky Live, a custom-designed webcam system that snaps magnetically to the top of the Glass TV and unlocks a slew of interactive experiences with your telly. With Sky Live, you're able to sign-in to an existing Zoom account and host meetings from the comfort of your sofa &ndash; with AI-powered software ensuring that you're always positioned correctly in the middle of the frame.</p><p>Sku Live also lets you watch live with friends and family spread across the country &ndash; with everyone's reactions to the show, sport fixture, or movie, available to see and hear in real-time. Motion-controlled games are included at no extra cost, and Sky has co-developed a dedicated fitness app called Mvmnt that corrects your form as you exercise.&nbsp;</p><p>Sky Glass can be bought outright &ndash; like any other new telly from a shop &ndash; or can be paid in monthly instalments with your chosen Sky TV bundle. This makes the upgrade more affordable. Like Sky Stream, your TV is a rolling monthly contract, so you can switch between packages, like Sky Cinema and Sky Sports, every 30-days or so.</p><p>If you stop subscribing to Sky TV entirely, you can continue to use Sky Glass to watch Freeview channels and streamers.</p><p>While it's possible to buy Sky Glass outright, the satellite company also offers its all-new QLED TV in small monthly ins